{
  "texts": [
    "There needs to be a holistic approach which provides a more comprehensive regulatory proposition than the frameworks deployed by the world's three digital empires: state-based (China), market-based (US), and rightsbased (EU) [48].As we explained in this work, it presents a far-fetched claim to have sentient machines that can understand themselves and the world around them, under the current mode of operation of LLMs.",
    "However, we must not exclude the possibility to have emergent phenomena which will lead to such an entity through other methods of simulating the human brain, for instance as a set of multiple neighborhood cellular automata [11] which can construct similar structures such as the \"other brain\" hypothesis we mentioned in the beginning of Materials and Methods section.",
    "Moving forward in this train of thought, if such an entity occurs, what rights should be appointed to it?",
    "Is it going to be considered a person?",
    "Or maybe something in between, with an a-la-carte relation to its human overlords depending on the use case it may serve?In this noteworthy case, provided that such an entity was being built and it had the capacity to store a human brain with all its intellect and capabilities inside it, it could be a case of achieving a type of \"digital immortality\"."
  ]
}